'''Trifluoromethylsulfur pentafluoride''', CF<sub>3</sub>SF<sub>5</sub>, is a rare industrial [[greenhouse gas]].<ref>{{cite book |first= Richard P. |last= Tuckett |title= Fluorine and the Environment Atmospheric Chemistry, Emissions, & Lithosphere (Advances in Fluorine Science series)|volume= 1 |year=2006 |publisher=Elsevier |isbn=0-444-52811-3 |pages=89–129 |chapter= Chapter 3: Trifluoromethyl Sulphur Pentafluoride, SF<sub>5</sub>CF<sub>3</sub>: Atmospheric Chemistry and Its Environmental Importance via the Greenhouse Effect |doi= 10.1016/S1872-0358(06)01003-7 |editor-first= Alain |editor-last= Tressaud}}</ref> It was first identified in the atmosphere in 2000.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Sturges|first=W.T. |author2=T. J. Wallington |author3=M. D. Hurley |author4=K. P. Shine |author5=K. Sihra |author6=A. Engel |author7=D. E. Oram |author8=S. A. Penkett |author9=R. Mulvaney |author10=C.A.M. Brenninkmeijer|title=A Potent Greenhouse Gas Identified in the Atmosphere: SF<sub>5</sub>CF<sub>3</sub>|journal=Science|date=28 July 2000|volume=289|issue=5479|pages=611–613|doi=10.1126/science.289.5479.611}}</ref> Trifluoromethylsulfur pentafluoride is considered to be one of the several "super-greenhouse gases". On a per molecule basis, it is considered to be the most potent greenhouse gas present in Earth's atmosphere, having a [[global warming potential]] of about 18,000 times that of [[carbon dioxide]].<ref name=MS2008>{{cite journal|last=Suen|first=Martin|title=Trifluoromethyl Sulfur Pentafluoride (CF<sub>3</sub>SF<sub>5</sub>): A Review of the Recently  Discovered Super-Greenhouse Gas in the Atmosphere|journal=The Open Atmospheric Science Journal|year=2008|volume=2|pages=56–60|doi=10.2174/1874282300802010056}}</ref> The chemical is predicted to have a lifetime of 800 years in the atmosphere.<ref>{{cite journal |journal= Journal of Hazardous Materials |volume= 149 |issue= 3 |year= 2007 |pages= 747–751 |title= The prediction of environmental fate for trifluoromethyl sulfur pentafluoride (CF<sub>3</sub>SF<sub>5</sub>), a potent greenhouse gas |first= Wen-Tien |last= Tsai |doi= 10.1016/j.jhazmat.2007.08.035 |pmid= 17884286 }}</ref> However, the current concentration of trifluoromethylsulfur pentafluoride remains at a level that is unlikely to measurably contribute to [[global warming]].<ref name=MS2008 /> The presence of the gas in the atmosphere is attributed to [[Human impact on the environment|anthropogenic]] sources, possibly a by-product of the manufacture of [[fluorochemical]]s, originating from reactions of SF<sub>6</sub> with fluoropolymers used in electronic devices and in microchips, or the formation can be associated with [[high voltage]] equipment created from SF<sub>6</sub> (a breakdown product of high voltage equipment) reacting with CF<sub>3</sub> to form the CF<sub>3</sub>SF<sub>5</sub> molecule.<ref name=MS2008 /> The chemistry of this compound is similar to that of [[sulfur hexafluoride]] (SF<sub>6</sub>).<ref>{{cite journal |title= Trifluoromethylsulfur Pentafluoride |first1= Gene A. |last1= Silvey |first2= George H. |last2= Cady |journal= J. Am. Chem. Soc. |year= 1950 |volume= 72 | issue= 8 |pages= 3624–3626 |doi= 10.1021/ja01164a084 }}</ref>

