{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}} {{Infobox aircraft occurrence |name = Turkish Airlines Flight 278 |occurrence_type = Accident |image = File:Boeing 737-4Y0, Turkish Airlines JP171975.jpg |caption = TC-JES, the aircraft involved the accident. |date = 29 December 1994 |type = [[Controlled flight into terrain]] |site = near [[Van Ferit Melen Airport]], Turkey |coordinates = {{Coord|38|24|00|N|43|13|48|E|type:event|display=inline,title}} |aircraft_type = [[Boeing 737 Classic|Boeing 737-4Y0]] |aircraft_name = ''Mersin'' |operator = [[Turkish Airlines]] |tail_number = TC-JES |origin = [[Esenboğa International Airport]], [[Ankara]], Turkey |destination = [[Van Ferit Melen Airport]], [[Van, Turkey|Van]], Turkey |passengers = 69 |crew = 7 |injuries = |fatalities = 57 |survivors = 19 }} {{Location map+ |Turkey |relief = 1 |border = |caption = Location of departure and destination airports |float = right |width = 350 |places = {{Location map~|Turkey|lat=40.1167|long=32.9833|position = left |label=Ankara Esenboğa Airport|label_size=80|marksize=6}} {{Location map~|Turkey|lat=38.475|long=43.317|position = bottom |label=Van Ferit Melen Airport|label_size=80|marksize=6}} }}
'''Turkish Airlines Flight 278''', operated by a [[Boeing 737|Boeing 737-4Y0]] registered TC-JES and named ''Mersin'', was a domestic scheduled flight from [[Esenboğa International Airport|Ankara Esenboğa Airport]] to [[Van Ferit Melen Airport]] in eastern [[Turkey]] that crashed on 29 December 1994 during its [[Final approach (aviation)|final approach]] to land in driving snow. Five of the seven crew and 52 of the 69 passengers lost their lives, while two crew members and 17 passengers survived with serious injuries.<ref name="asn">{{cite web |url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19941229-0 |publisher=Aviation Safety Network |title=Aircraft accident description |accessdate=1 January 2009 }}</ref>
==Aircraft== The aircraft, a [[Boeing 737-400|Boeing 737-4Y0]] with two [[CFM International CFM56#CFM56-3 series|CFMI CFM56-3C1]] [[jet engine]]s, was built by [[Boeing]] with manufacturer serial number 26074/2376,<ref name="asn" /> and made its first flight on 25 September 1992.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.airfleets.net/ficheapp/plane-b737-26074.htm |publisher=Air Fleets |title=Boeing 737 MSN 26074 |accessdate=1 January 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.planespotters.net/Production_List/Boeing/737/26074,TC-JES-Turkish-Airlines.php |title=TC-JES Turkish Airlines Boeing 737-4Y0 – cn 26074 / ln 2376 – Planespotters.net Just Aviation |publisher=Planespotters.net |date= |accessdate=13 January 2014}}</ref>
==Crash== At 15:30 [[Eastern European Time|EET]] (13:30 [[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]]), TK278 struck a hill near [[Edremit (District), Van|Edremit]] district of [[Van Province]] at {{convert|5700|ft|m|abbr=on}} [[above mean sea level|AMSL]] around {{convert|4|km|nmi|abbr=on}} from Van Airport while on a third [[VHF omnidirectional range|VOR]]-[[Distance measuring equipment|DME]] approach to the Runway 03 in bad weather despite a warning from [[air traffic control]] not to attempt any more approaches in a snowstorm. The visibility was {{convert|900|m|ft|abbr=on}} reducing to {{convert|300|m|ft|abbr=on}} in heavy driving snow.<ref name="asn" /><ref name="byegm">{{cite web |url=http://www.byegm.gov.tr/YAYINLARIMIZ/AyinTarihi/1994/aralik1994.htm |publisher=Governmental Press and Information Office |title=Aralık 1994 |language=Turkish |accessdate=1 January 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.flightglobal.com/articles/1995/01/04/28166/turkey-crash.html |publisher=Flight Global |title=Turkey crash |date=4 January 1995 |accessdate=1 January 2008}}</ref>
It was the worst aviation accident involving a Boeing 737-400 at that time. It was subsequently surpassed by [[Adam Air Flight 574]] which crashed on 1 January 2007 with 102 fatalities, and fourth worst aircraft accident in Turkey at that time.<ref name="asn" />
==Crew and passengers== The aircraft had a crew of 7 and 69 passengers including two babies.<ref name="byegm" /> Two of the crew and 17 passengers survived the crash with serious injuries.<ref name="asn" />
